Fig. 2
 showed the fluorescence spectra of M-GQDs complex with different biothiol concentrations. It was obvious that the fluorescence intensity of M-GQDs complex in the absence of biothiol was very weak. While with addition of biothiol, the maleimide group reacted with the mercaptan group (-SH) in the side chain of the biothiol residue [33] through Michael addition reaction, which led to the fluorescence recovery of GQDs. The crosslinking of the maleimide unit (electron acceptance group) to the electron donor GQDs will quenched the fluorescence of M-GQDs. In the sensing process, the fluorescence intensity of M-GQDs increased when different concentrations of Cys or GSH were added to the system as test analytes, (Fig. 3
). Because the interaction between M-GQDs probes and different kinds of biological thiols (Cys or GSH) led to the conversion of double bonds of maleimide rings into saturated maleimide rings through Michael addition reaction, which inactivated intramolecular charge transfer (ICT) and photoinduced electron transfer (PET) processed and destroyed the horses attached to the surface of GQDs. The quenching ability of the leimide domain further resulted in the fluorescence of GQDs restoring to the “ON” state (Scheme 1A). As shown in Fig. 2, the fluorescence intensity of M-GQDs gradually increased with the increased biothiol concentration. A good linearity was observed between I/I0 (I and I0 referred to the fluorescence intensity of M-GQDs complex with or without of GSH, respectively) and biothiol concentrations of 5.0 × 10−9 - 4.0 × 10−7 mol/L (Fig. 2b). The regression equation was I/I0 = 1.44 + 0.04logCGSH (mol/L), (R2 = 0.998) and the detection limit was 1.69 × 10−9 mol/L.
